Subject: definition
Value: <2012-04-05: Barry SmithThe official OBI definition, explaining the meaning of a class or property: 'Shall be Aristotelian, formalized and normalized. Can be augmented with colloquial definitions' is terrible.Can you fix to something like:A statement of necessary and sufficient conditions explaining the meaning of an expression referring to a class or property.Alan RuttenbergYour proposed definition is a reasonable candidate, except that it is very common that necessary and sufficient conditions are not given. Mostly they are necessary, occasionally they are necessary and sufficient or just sufficient. Often they use terms that are not themselves defined and so they effectively can't be evaluated by those criteria. On the specifics of the proposed definition:We don't have definitions of 'meaning' or 'expression' or 'property'. For 'reference' in the intended sense I think we use the term 'denotation'. For 'expression', I think we you mean symbol, or identifier. For 'meaning' it differs for class and property. For class we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine whether an entity is instance of the class, or not. For property we want documentation that let's the intended reader determine, given a pair of potential relata, whether the assertion that the relation holds is true. The 'intended reader' part suggests that we also specify who, we expect, would be able to understand the definition, and also generalizes over human and computer reader to include textual and logical definition. Personally, I am more comfortable weakening definition to documentation, with instructions as to what is desirable. We also have the outstanding issue of how to aim different definitions to different audiences. A clinical audience reading chebi wants a different sort of definition documentation/definition from a chemistry trained audience, and similarly there is a need for a definition that is adequate for an ontologist to work with. @en>

Value: piwi-1+, lhx1/5-1+, pitx+ progenitor neoblasts required for specification of tph+ serotonergic neurons.

Subject: klf+ sensory neuron progenitor cell
Value: piwi-1+, klf+ progenitor neoblasts required for production of cintillo+ sensory neurons.

Subject: pax3/7+ neural progenitor cell
Value: piwi-1+, pax3/7+ progenitor neoblasts implicated in the production of DBH+ ventral midline neurons.

Subject: participates in
Value: a relation between a continuant and a process, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: has participant
Value: a relation between a process and a continuant, in which the continuant is somehow involved in the process@en

Subject: derives from
Value: a relation between two distinct material entities, the new entity and the old entity, in which the new entity begins to exist when the old entity ceases to exist, and the new entity inherits the significant portion of the matter of the old entity@en

Subject: derives into
Value: a relation between two distinct material entities, the old entity and the new entity, in which the new entity begins to exist when the old entity ceases to exist, and the new entity inherits the significant portion of the matter of the old entity@en

Subject: has component process
Value: w 'has process component' p if p and w are processes,  w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: overlaps
Value: x overlaps y if and only if there exists some z such that x has part z and z part of y

Subject: overlaps
Value: x overlaps y iff they have some part in common.

Subject: has component
Value: w 'has component' p if w 'has part' p and w is such that it can be directly disassembled into into n parts p, p2, p3, ..., pn, where these parts are of similar type.

Subject: develops from
Value: x develops from y if and only if either (a) x directly develops from y or (b) there exists some z such that x directly develops from z and z develops from y

Subject: develops_into
Value: inverse of develops from

Subject: regulates
Value: <process(P1) regulates process(P2) iff: P1 results in the initiation or termination of P2 OR affects the frequency of its initiation or termination OR affects the magnitude or rate of output of P2.>

Subject: capable of part of
Value: c stands in this relationship to p if and only if there exists some p' such that c is capable_of p', and p' is part_of p.

Subject: adjacent_to
Value: x adjacent to y if and only if x and y share a boundary.

Subject: adjacent_to
Value: <x adjacent_to y iff: x and y share a boundary>

Subject: has input
has developmental contribution from
Value: x has developmental contribution from y iff x has some part z such that z develops from y@en

Subject: developmentally contributes to
Value: inverse of has developmental contribution from

Subject: acts upstream of
Value: c acts upstream of p if and only if c enables some f that is involved in p' and p' occurs chronologically before p, is not part of p, and affects the execution of p. c is a material entity and f, p, p' are processes.

Subject: acts upstream of or within
Value: c acts upstream of or within p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of or within p. c is a material entity and p is an process.

Subject: part of structure that is capable of
Value: this relation holds between c and p when c is part of some c', and c' is capable of p.

Subject: involved in
Value: c involved_in p if and only if c enables some process p', and p' is part of p

Subject: enabled by
Value: inverse of enables

Subject: regulated by
Value: inverse of regulates

Subject: negatively regulated by
Value: inverse of negatively regulates

Subject: positively regulated by
Value: inverse of positively regulates

Subject: input of
Value: inverse of has input

Subject: has developmental potential involving
Value: x has developmental potential involving y iff x is capable of a developmental process with output y. y may be the successor of x, or may be a different structure in the vicinity (as for example in the case of developmental induction).@en

Subject: has potential to developmentally contribute to
Value: x has potential to developmentrally contribute to y iff x developmentally contributes to y or x is capable of developmentally contributing to y@en

Subject: has potential to develop into
Value: x has the potential to develop into y iff x develops into y or if x is capable of developing into y@en

Subject: has potential to directly develop into
Value: x has potential to directly develop into y iff x directly develops into y or x is capable of directly developing into y@en

Subject: causally downstream of
Value: inverse of upstream of

Subject: causally upstream of
Value: p is causally upstream of q if and only if p precedes q and p and q are linked in a causal chain

Subject: immediately causally upstream of
Value: p is immediately causally upstream of q iff both (a) p immediately precedes q and (b) p is causally upstream of q. In addition, the output of p  must be an input of q.

Subject: causally upstream of or within
Value: p 'causally upstream or within' q iff (1) the end of p is before the end of q and (2) the execution of p exerts some causal influence over the outputs of q; i.e. if p was abolished or the outputs of p were to be modified, this would necessarily affect q.

Subject: causally downstream of or within
Value: inverse of causally upstream of or within

Subject: involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' regulates some p

Subject: involved in positive regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' positively regulates some p

Subject: involved in negative regulation of
Value: c involved in regulation of p if c is involved in some p' and p' negatively regulates some p

Subject: involved in or involved in regulation of
Value: c involved in or regulates p if and only if either (i) c is involved in p or (ii) c is involved in regulation of p

Subject: is active in
Value: c executes activity in d if and only if c enables p and p occurs_in d.  Assuming no action at a distance by gene products, if a gene product enables (is capable of) a process that occurs in some structure, it must have at least some part in that structure.

Subject: has part that occurs in
Value: p has part that occurs in c if and only if there exists some p1, such that p has_part p1, and p1 occurs in c.

Subject: existence overlaps
Value: <x existence overlaps y if and only if either (a) the start of x is part of y or (b) the end of x is part of y. Formally: x existence starts and ends during y iff (α(x) >= α(y) & α(x) <= ω(y)) OR (ω(x) <= ω(y) & ω(x) >= α(y))>

Subject: existence starts during or after
Value: <x existence starts during or after y if and only if the time point at which x starts is after or equivalent to the time point at which y starts. Formally: x existence starts during or after y iff α (x) >= α (y).>

Subject: existence ends during or before
Value: x existence ends during or before y if and only if the time point at which x ends is before or equivalent to the time point at which y ends.

Subject: causal relation between processes
Value: p is causally related to q if and only if p or any part of p and q or any part of q are linked by a chain of events where each event pair is one of direct activation or direct inhibition. p may be upstream, downstream, part of or a container of q.

Subject: is indirect form of
Value: <relation p is the indirect form of relation q iff p is a subPropertyOf q, and there exists some p' such that p' is the direct form of q, p' o p' -> p, and forall x,y : x q y -> either (1) x p y or (2) x p' y>

Subject: has part structure that is capable of
Value: s 'has part structure that is capable of' p if and only if there exists some part x such that s 'has part' x and x 'capable of' p

Subject: produces
Value: <a produces b if some process that occurs_in a has_output b, where a and b are material entities. Examples: hybridoma cell line produces monoclonal antibody reagent; chondroblast produces avascular GAG-rich matrix.>

Subject: produced_by
Value: a produced_by b iff some process that occurs_in b has_output a.

Subject: acts upstream of, positive effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, positive effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is positive

Subject: acts upstream of, negative effect
Value: c 'acts upstream of, negative effect' p if c is enables f, and f is causally upstream of p, and the direction of f is negative

Subject: parallel to
Value: x is parallel t y iff x and y are lines or planes which when extended indefinitely do not cross.
